INFLUENZA, INCREASED CASE LOAD - USA (02)
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Influenza, increased case load - USA 980110230805
Influenza, increased case load - USA (California)(02) 980113011534
[1
Date: Wed, 14 Jan 1998 00:41:33 -0800
From: Dr. James Chin, CDPC-mail
Source: Nando net, January 14, 1998

Fifteen states have reported influenza outbreaks, a 50% increase from a
week earlier, federal health officials said Tuesday. The Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said flu activity was widespread in
New York, Tennessee and Texas during the week ended Jan. 3. Flu outbreaks
were also reported in Alabama, Arizona, California, Colorado, Connecticut,
Hawaii, Maryland, Michigan, Mississippi, Pennsylvania, South Dakota and
Virginia, the CDC said. These 15 states reported flu outbreaks during the
week ended Jan. 3, the latest date for which figures were available. A week
earlier, 10 states were reporting outbreaks. Influenza type A has been
reported in 47 states. The type A cases include a new "Sydney" flu strain
first detected in Australia and New Zealand in June. Four states and the
District of Columbia have reported type B flu, the CDC said. Other states
reported only sporadic cases of flu-like illness, while North Dakota and
Oregon reported no flu activity. The CDC said the flu season generally
peaks between January and March. Health officials estimate that influenza
is associated with about 20,000 deaths nationwide every year.
--
