[2
Date: Tue, 13 Jan 1998 08:29:29 EST
From: Ray Weinstein <AlaskaRay@aol.com>

I would have to say that the situation here in Northern Virginia is similar
to that in Los Angeles, California [see 980113011534. In our three
offices and in the E.R., we're seeing some cases of influenza but I suspect
that the unseasonably warm weather we've been enjoying is going to delay
the full impact of our flu season. Mostly we're seeing a severe upper
respiratory infection consisting of congestion, dry cough, headache, and
low-grade fever which is lasting 10 to 14 days. Often the cough lingers
for weeks after the illness has subsided.
--
Ray Weinstein, M.D.
Medical Director, Potomac Family Health
Dale City, Va.
e-mail: AlaskaRay@aol.com
[By convention, influenza viruses are designated by their serotype/host
species/site of origin/month and year of origin/and (H and N subtype). Thus
(example only; I am not making policy here), A/Chicken/Hong Kong/5/97(H5N1)
if I am not mistaken. The so-called "Sydney" strain is an H3N2 subtype.
Please pardon us if at times we use "slang" because of carelessness or the
lateness of the hour. - Mod.CHC
